Callback Rates and Unemployment in 11 States¶

About the Data¶

The motivations for these projects are tied directly to my position as an RA for the CCEAI. This project is based on four different data sources. The main dataset is from the paper ‘Is It Harder for Older Workers to Find Jobs? New and Improved Evidence from a Field Experiment’ (1). The data enrichment is done with State Unemployment Percentage (2), GeoPy Nonimatim (3) and Age Discrimination Laws per state from the paper "Do State Laws Protecting Older Workers from Discrimination Reduce Age Discrimination in Hiring? Evidence from a Field Experiment" (4). As a note (4) was manually interpreted from the page 16 table on these laws, and binary encoded. For further insights, that csv file can be found in the data folder under the name 'StateLawsAge.csv" The main dataset contains 40,208 resume applications, that were generated for a correspondence study to uncover age discrimination in job application. These resumes are based on real world resumes, and more information on their generation process can be found in (1). These resumes were used to apply to real job applications across 11 states, and each application was done in sets of three, one from each agegroup. So for each ad, three comparable applications were sent, their only notable difference was the age of the applicant. Hence, the generated resumes have been formulated to have as many controlled variables as possible, and to seem as realistic as possible. Each resume contains the applicants name, age, contact information, the job they applied to, their skill level, educational background, special skills, city and whether they got a callback. For each application, the main measurement (and in this analysis case the target variable to predict) is whether the applicant (resume) received a callback.

The unemployment percentage data is from the bureau of labor statistics and contains the employment and unemployment percentage for each respective state for each year. As the main data concerns only 2015, that is the only year that is appended to the data.

GeoPy Nonimatim is used to fetch the state for each city, as the resume applications contain only the city where the application was made. As the application corresponds to the location of the applicant, we only need to fetch one states information per application.

The final enrichment dataset is from the paper "Do State Laws Protecting Older Workers from Discrimination Reduce Age Discrimination in Hiring? Evidence from a Field Experiment" (4), and were manually extracted and then encoded to be categorical and binary.

Research Questions, Treatments, and Measures¶

  • 1.Is there a relationship between the age group and callbacks?
  • 2.Can we predict callbacks, and how accurately can we do this?
  • 3.Does age affect the callback prediction between the groups?
  • 4.How can we make the callback rates fair between the groups?

The data was divided into an 80/20 split, with 20% as testing data that contains the original distribution of the data. This is done using stratified sampling. The remaining 80% is divided into several datasets to train Logistic Regression, Random Forest and MLP classifiers on. Each classifier was trained with the five datasets.

Treatments¶

Base Rate (BR)¶
  • Original data distribution
Fewer Young/Middle (FWYM)¶
  • Randomly delete young/middle-aged people, at 30%.
Equalized Base Rate (EBR)¶
  • Randomly delete old people that did not get a callback, so that the callback rate matches that of young/middle.
Higher Base Rate Difference (HBRD)¶
  • Randomly delete young/middle-aged people that did not get a callback, at 30%, so that the callback rate matches that of old.
Balanced outcomes (BO)¶
  • Down sample young and middle age groups so that the number of callbacks matches that of old people.

There are five measurements used for each of these five sets, to measure the level of bias for each group. These are from the papers (6) and (7). The notation $_(ym)$ refers to tthe combined age group of young and middle. Meanwhile, the notation $ _(old) $ refers to the old age group. All measures are done as the difference between the results of these two groups.

Measures¶

Demographic Parities¶
  • Receiving positive outcomes at the same rate, so $ \frac{(TP_(old)+FP_(old))}{(TP_(old)+FP_(old)+FN_(old)+TN_(old))} - \frac{(TP_(ym)+FP_(ym))}{(TP_(ym)+FP_(ym)+FN_(ym)+TN_(ym))} $
Demographic Parities Gap¶
  • The division of accurate outcomes between the two groups $ \frac{(TP_(old)+TN_(old))} {(TP_(old)+FP_(old)+FN_(old)+TN_(old))} - \frac{(TP_(ym)+TN_(ym))}{(TP_(ym)+FP_(ym)+FN_(ym)+TN_(ym))} $
Equalized Odds¶
  • Equal True Positive and False Positive rates between the two different groups match, so $ \frac{(TP_(old))}{(TP_(old)+FP_(old)+FN_(old)+TN_(old))} - \frac{(TP_(ym))}{(TP_(ym)+FP_(ym)+FN_(ym)+TN_(ym))} $ and $ \frac{(FP_(old))}{(TP_(old)+FP_(old)+FN_(old)+TN_(old))} - \frac{(FP_(ym))}{(TP_(ym)+FP_(ym)+FN_(ym)+TN_(ym))} $
Predictive Rate Parity¶
  • Whether a classifiers precision rates are equivalent for subgroups under consideration.
AUC-ROC¶
  • AUC (Area Under The Curve) ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristics) curve.

The aim here is to see how strong the effet of age is on the callback rates, how do rebalancing and data manipulationg affect the learning outcomes for Logistic Regression, Random Forest and MLP. These three ML models were chosen to be able to compare between treatments and measures more accurately, and to balance the effect of the model.

5 rows × 138 columns

Above is the raw data, which has 138 columns. From a cursory glance, it can be seen that the data is not very neat and there is a lot of redundant data. There are multiple dummy columns - for example the age group, and separate 'middlemale', 'oldmale', 'oldfemale', 'middlefemale' and many others. This pattern of extra columns and irregular format is consistent in the data, so the first step is to clean these up.

As can be seen, the adtititles are in need of cleaning, and as aforementioned there are some duplicate columns, and irrelevant columns that need to be dropped. We also combine some of the columns, to remove redundancy. The columns that are used in the end are 'state', 'zipcode','city','agegroup', 'gender', 'employment', 'occupation','template', 'spanish','extra_qualifs', 'internshipflag', 'customerservice', 'cpr', 'techskills', 'wpm', 'grammar', 'college', 'employeemonth', 'volunteer', 'skill', 'callback', 'adtitle'. There is also the question of missing data, as the data has the city, but no state. So we use geopy Nonimatim to add the state based on the city. We need to create dummies later to be able to run the ML models, but at the moment we are just striving for a clean dataset that can be used for different purposes. Further cleaning and its details can be found in the helper_scripts.py that is imported in the beginning.

Above are the state laws for age discrimination.

The additional data enrichement is done with State laws for Age Discrimination. This data can be found in (4) in table form, as was aforementioned - that data was manually parsed into a csv, and then encoded into categorical and binary form depending on the column.

Additionally, this dataset was enriched with the unemployment percentages for each state. These extra columns are 'hs_diploma_state', 'college_diploma_state', 'some_college_state','unemployment_perc', 'ADL Minimum Firm Size', 'ADL Larger Damages than ADEA', 'DDL Minimum Firm Size','DDL Larger Damages than ADA','DDL Broader Definition of Disability'.

These correspond to the the rate of high school graduation, college graduation rate, college attendance rate, state unemployment percentage, the minimum firm size for the age discrimination laws to apply, whether these ADL damages are larger than The Age Discrimination in Employment Act damages, Disability Discrimination Act Damages larger than ADA, and whether DDL has a broader definition of disability. As a precursor here it is important to remember the state vs. federal laws. While there are federal level laws, state laws might be more punitive.

The above two graphs show the z-scored callback rates per employment sector per state, the first one shows bars and we separate state and skill levels. The second graph takes across all states and just shows the general z-scored distribution for the data, to give more emphasis on the relationship between the unemployment percentage and the callback rates. By z-scoring the unemployment data, we can see that when we compare a states statistics to the mean, that among the states we have multiple outliers. However, we can only really make some assumptions based on these and we can not comment on the causation of these deviations.

For Graph 1, the unemployment percentage on the y-axis being negative is desirable as it means the states unemployment percentage is lower than the mean. Meanwhile, for the callback rates on the y-axis, a positive value is more desirable. There does not seem to be a clear indication that the unemployment percentage has a relationship with the number of callback received. We can see that between states, the labor market is very different, for example Pennsylvania there seems to be a high demand for highly educated employed administrative personnel. In New York, despite a higher education it is much more difficult and unlikely to receive a callback. For Utah, an applicant is more likely to receive a callback no matter the education level.

For Graph 2, we can see that there is some effect where when unemployment rates are at the mean or slightly above it, the callback rates are below the mean. However, this effect is not continous and does not constitute a trend. So, there is some relationship where deviation from the mean employment irregardless of it being negative or positive results in a boost in callback rates on average. This is difficult to say what is causing it, as the local labor market distribution is not being taken into account.

Machine Learning¶

As mentioned before, the three chosen models are Logistic Regression, Random Forest Regression and Multilayer Perceptron. These three models are ran for each treatment, and their results for the measurements are collected in a dictionary. The analysis and results can be found at the bottom, but note that each run will show the AUC-ROC for the model, 5-fold cross validation,10-fold cross validation, and the True and False Positive/Negative rates. The distributions for the test data are taken with a stratified sample, so the test data is representative of the underlying distribution. As was aforementioned, the expirements are using a 80/20 split.

def analytics(analytics_dict):
    """demographic parity ; receiving positive outcomes at the same rate,
    the demographic parity gap; difference in the two groups parities, 
    the accuracy parity ; the division of accurate outcomes between the two groups, 
    equalized odds ; that equal true positive and false positive rates between the two different groups match,
    predictive rate parity; whether a classifiers precision rates are equivalent for subgroups under consideration.
    """
    keys_t = ''
    keys = ''                                                                                                                   
    dp_str = ''
    for key_t in analytics_dict.keys():
        keys_t += '\t' + key_t
        model_dict = analytics_dict[key_t]
        ti_k = '\t '

        for key in model_dict.keys():
            ti_k += f'{key_t} {key} {key_t} \t'
            dp_str +=  f' {key_t} {key}: {np.round(model_dict[key]["dp_parity"], 3)},\t'
        dp_str+= '\n'
    print('Demographic parities')
    print('Receiving positive outcomes at the same rate (difference in the two groups parities) -- Equal Positive Prediction Rates ')
    print(keys)
    print(dp_str)
        
    
    dp_str_gp = ''
    for key_t in analytics_dict.keys():       
        model_dict = analytics_dict[key_t]

        for key in model_dict.keys():
            ti_k += f'{key_t} {key} {key_t} \t'
            dp_str_gp +=  f'{key_t} {key}: {np.round(model_dict[key]["dp_parity_gap"], 3)}: \t'
        dp_str_gp += '\n'
    print('\nDemographic parities gap for', key_t)
    print('The division of accurate outcomes between the two groups')
    print('\t', keys)
    print(dp_str_gp)

    dp_str_TP = ''
    dp_str_FP = ''
    for key_t in analytics_dict.keys():

        for key in model_dict.keys():
            dp_str_TP += f'TP {key_t} {key}: {np.round(model_dict[key]["TP_dif"], 3)} , '

        dp_str_TP += '\n'
        dp_str_FP += '\n'
    print('\nEqualised Odds')
    print('Equal true positive and false positive rates between the two different groups match')
    print('\t', keys)
    print(dp_str_TP, '\n', dp_str_FP)
    
    dp_str_precision = ''

            roc_auc += f'{key_t}, {key1}: {np.round(prev[key1]["AUC"], 3)}\t'

Above are the results for the five measurements for each dataset and ML model.

As can be seen, the baserate is at 0.2-0.9% for demographic parities. Meanwhile, for the demographic parities gap the base rate is at -2.4% - -4.8%. For Equalised odds, the base rate is at 0.2% - -1.4%, and the predictive rate parity is at 5% - 7.5%. The ROC AUC is at 50%- 52.8% All the comparisons are done against these statistics. For all measurements but the AUC, closer to zero is considered better. For AUC the higher is better.

For the Demographic parities, the base rate performs the best, while for the demographic parities gap the higher base rate does the best. For Equalised odds, the best performance is the higher base rate. For Predictive rate parity, the best result on the other hand is the base rate. For the AUC, the higher base rate performs the best. Overall, across the five measurements the best model is Random Forest Classifier with the higher baserate dataset, as it is performs the best at 3/5 measurements.

For some reason, the Logistic Regression (LR) seems to predict everything as a negative, while the Random Forest (RF) is more considerate of the Positives. MLP has a similar issue as the Logistic Regression, but it is overall predicting some callbacks. Overall the goal of predictions would be to hire people, so the false positive callbacks are more acceptable than the false negatives. A model like this should not be making final decisions, so the false positives would still be getting a chance of a callback, and these false positives would be culled out later in the manual portion of the hiring process. Unfortunately the rate of False Negatives is high across all three models which is resulting in applicants, who should be receiving them, not receiving callbacks. The LR and MLP especially might be overfitting as there is a large class imbalance of no callback.

Across the measurements no one is getting favoured excessively, and actual callbacks are being done to all age groups with only percentage margins. Instead, all groups are treated in a comparable manner, and the applicants are receiving callbacks for RDR. Overall, the Random Forest Classifier is the most suitable model for the task, as the prediction accuracy is comparable, and the type of error is more acceptable when compared to the two other models. However, more optimization is needed.

As a limitation, it must be noted that the test set is representative of the underlying distribution but is not the exact same test set for each experiment. Unfortunately, I realised this fact only the day the project was due and hence did not want to risk running it all again. So, these results are not entirely conclusive, but they do give direction as afterall the test set is representative of the underlying distribution and there is only one target variable (callback). Additionally, the rates for the treatments of Higher Base Rate and Fewer Young/Middle Age only include the 30%, and it is unclear whether higher, or lower, percentages have a greater effect on the populus.
